</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">for an accomodation he must come himself as they were fully determined to prevent deception by lending no ear to any body else.  They allowed <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Le Rouge</span> Two moons for consideration.  The Ambassadors assured the chiefs that Le Rouge had the greatest desire for the restoration of cordiality between the contending tribes and would lose no opportunity which promised to effect so desirable an object as the reunion of the parties in peace and friendship.  Thus ended an affair which we suspected would have been concluded in the death of the Strangers from the bustle and confusion their arrival had occassioned.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">But I was informed afterwards that upon such occasions no danger is to be apprehended as Indians make it a point of honour to protect any Strangers, even their enemies, let alone Ambassadors who throw themselves on their clemency<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Towards evening the hollowing and hooping of the Young men who were on the top of the huts announced the appearance and approach of a hunting party of Mandanes consisting of One hundred men on horseBack all loaded with the spoils of the field after a days absence.  These people never go out Singly to hunt for <span class="AddHand-author">several</span> reasons </p>
<p style="text-align:right;">one</p>

